            <fr:anchor>9271</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-018D</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-018D.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Kleene’s theorem and its consequences">Kleene’s theorem and its consequences</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>We now come to the main result of this lecture.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7385</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-018B</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-018B.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Kleene’s theorem">Kleene’s theorem</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> is <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link> if and only if it is <fr:link href="jms-0185.xml" title="Automatical language" addr="jms-0185" type="local">automatical</fr:link>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7384</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6110</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6110.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>By <fr:link href="jms-018A.xml" title="All regular languages are automatical" addr="jms-018A" type="local">Corollary <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-018A" /></fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-0183.xml" title="Decompilation of NFAs" addr="jms-0183" type="local">Corollary <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-0183" /></fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>In light of the above, we will from now on refer mainly to <fr:link href="jms-018A.xml" title="All regular languages are automatical" addr="jms-018A" type="local">regular languages</fr:link>, and leave behind the non-standard terminology of <fr:link href="jms-0185.xml" title="Automatical language" addr="jms-0185" type="local">“automatical languages”</fr:link>. Several questions that we left unanswered (see <fr:link href="jms-017F.xml" title="Questions about regular expression matching" addr="jms-017F" type="local">Discussion <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-017F" /></fr:link>) can now be addressed in light of <fr:link href="jms-018B.xml" title="Kleene’s theorem" addr="jms-018B" type="local">Kleene’s theorem</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7387</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-018E</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-018E.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Decidability of regular expression matching">Decidability of <fr:link href="jms-017C.xml" title="Regular expression matching" addr="jms-017C" type="local">regular expression matching</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="jms-0179.xml" title="Regular expressions (abstract syntax)" addr="jms-0179" type="local">regular expression</fr:link> over an <fr:link href="jms-016H.xml" title="Alphabet" addr="jms-016H" type="local">alphabet</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists an algorithm to compute whether a given <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in \Sigma ^\star ]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="jms-017D.xml" title="The matching relation for regular expressions" addr="jms-017D" type="local">matches</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7386</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6111</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6111.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>The idea of the proof is to find a <fr:link href="jms-017L.xml" title="Deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">DFA</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> satisfying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}=\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>; so for this we need only <fr:link href="jms-018A.xml" title="All regular languages are automatical" addr="jms-018A" type="local">Corollary <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-018A" /></fr:link> rather than the full <fr:link href="jms-018B.xml" title="Kleene’s theorem" addr="jms-018B" type="local">Kleene’s theorem</fr:link>. Then our algorithm is to feed the given string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> through <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> and check whether the final state is accepting or not.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>There is a subtlety in the argument above: we need the <fr:link href="jms-017L.xml" title="Deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">DFA</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> to have computably decidable equality of states. The way to deal with this is that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> has a <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local"><fr:em>finite</fr:em></fr:link> set of states, and so <fr:link href="jms-00L0.xml" title="Isomorphic sets" addr="jms-00L0" type="local">isomorphic</fr:link> to a standard finite set of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}_{<n}]]></fr:tex>, which has computably decidable equality. A more important subtlety is that we need it to be computably decidable whether a given state is an accepting state, and we also need the transition function to be computable; any subset of a finite set is going to be decidable for roughly the same reason—ahead of time, we can enumerate it as a list of numbers in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}_{<n}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
