                <fr:title text="Closure of regular languages under intersection">Closure of <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular languages</fr:link> under intersection</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The intersection of two <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular languages</fr:link> over a fixed <fr:link href="jms-016H.xml" title="Alphabet" addr="jms-016H" type="local">alphabet</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7390</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6113</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6113.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We fix <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular languages</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L_1,L_2\subseteq \Sigma ^\star ]]></fr:tex> and consider the intersection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L_1\cap  L_2]]></fr:tex>. By De Morgan’s laws, we have:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  L_1\cap  L_2 =
  \Sigma ^\star \setminus {\mathopen {}\left (
   {\mathopen {}\left (
    \Sigma ^\star \setminus  L_1
   \right )\mathclose {}}\cup  {\mathopen {}\left (
    \Sigma ^\star \setminus  L_2
   \right )\mathclose {}}
  \right )\mathclose {}}
 ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>Because <fr:link href="jms-018F.xml" title="Closure of regular languages under complementation" addr="jms-018F" type="local"><fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular languages</fr:link> are closed under complementation</fr:link>, it suffices to check that <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
   {\mathopen {}\left (
    \Sigma ^\star \setminus  L_1
   \right )\mathclose {}}\cup  {\mathopen {}\left (
    \Sigma ^\star \setminus  L_2
   \right )\mathclose {}}
 ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link>. <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">Regular languages</fr:link> are, by definition, closed under finite unions, so it remains to check that the complements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^\star \setminus  L_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^\star \setminus  L_2]]></fr:tex> are <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link>. This follows from our assumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L_2]]></fr:tex> are <fr:link href="jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link> via <fr:link href="jms-018F.xml" title="Closure of regular languages under complementation" addr="jms-018F" type="local">closure under complements</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7393</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-018H</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-018H.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Decidability of regular expression equivalence">Decidability of <fr:link href="jms-0178.xml" title="Regular expressions" addr="jms-0178" type="local">regular expression</fr:link> equivalence</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>It is decidable whether two regular expressions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R,S]]></fr:tex> over a fixed <fr:link href="jms-016H.xml" title="Alphabet" addr="jms-016H" type="local">alphabet</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> are equivalent in the sense that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}=\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7392</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6114</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6114.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We note that two subsets are equal if and only if the intersection of one with the complement of the other is empty, and vice versa:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \begin {aligned}
   & \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}=\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &\quad \Leftrightarrow 
   \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}\subseteq \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}\land  \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}\subseteq \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &\quad \Leftrightarrow 
   {\mathopen {}\left ({\mathopen {}\left (\Sigma ^\star \setminus \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}\cap \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}} =\varnothing  = {\mathopen {}\left ({\mathopen {}\left (\Sigma ^\star \setminus \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}\cap \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
  \end {aligned}
 ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>We therefore let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> be two <fr:link href="jms-017L.xml" title="Deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">DFAs</fr:link> recognising the language <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\Sigma ^\star \setminus \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}\cap \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\Sigma ^\star \setminus \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}\cap \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> respectively. (These <fr:link href="jms-017L.xml" title="Deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">DFAs</fr:link> can be obtained computably using the compilation procedure by which we proved <fr:link href="jms-018A.xml" title="All regular languages are automatical" addr="jms-018A" type="local">Corollary <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-018A" /></fr:link>.) It follows then that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}=\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (S\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}=\varnothing =\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (N\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>So it now remains to check whether there exists <fr:em>any</fr:em> <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> at all that is accepted by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> and likewise for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex>. We do not have to check <fr:em>all</fr:em> <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">strings</fr:link> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>, which would be impossible: we observe that the number of states in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> bounds the number of transitions required to reach an accepting state, because any loops about a state <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> can be excised from the path without changing the result. This is a special property of the <fr:link href="jms-017J.xml" title="Kinds of finite automata" addr="jms-017J" type="local">finite automata</fr:link> that we have studied so far, corresponding to the fact that they have no memory.</fr:p>

</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
